ich each group can serve as a driver of green growth. Then, Lenox and Chatterji identify where economic incentives currently exist, or could exist with institutional change, and ultimately address the larger question of how far well-coordinated efforts can take us in addressing the current environmental crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBusiness enterprisesxEnvironmental aspects. 0aIndustrial managementxEnvironmental aspects. 0aSustainable development. 0aTechnological innovationsxEnvironmental aspects. 4abusiness. 4acorporate social responsibility. 4aenvironment. 4ainnovation. 4asustainability. 4atechnology. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Green Business.2bisacsh1 aChatterji, Aaron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360619740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503606197423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503606197.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles